{"uid":"890d9b5a83d29cc6","name":"test_patroni_reinit_after_pg_control_deletion","fullName":"tests.integration.high_availability.test_patroni_reinit#test_patroni_reinit_after_pg_control_deletion","historyId":"ff0bd7d4cafca3f063aea6eb40602f41","time":{"start":1779847369385,"stop":1779847412193,"duration":42808},"description":"Verify a replica reinitialises correctly after pg_control deletion and patronictl reinit.\n\n    Steps:\n    1. Confirm the cluster is healthy and continuous writes are flowing.\n    2. Stop Patroni on a replica, delete pg_control, then restart Patroni so that\n       PostgreSQL fails to start due to the missing control file.\n    3. Verify pebble logs on the replica record a pg_control startup failure.\n    4. Run ``patronictl reinit`` inside the replica container to restore it from the primary.\n    5. Confirm the replica recovers, that pg_control is present in the data directory,\n       and that data integrity is maintained across all units.\n    ","descriptionHtml":"<p>Verify a replica reinitialises correctly after pg_control deletion and patronictl reinit.</p>\n<pre><code>Steps:\n1. Confirm the cluster is healthy and continuous writes are flowing.\n2. Stop Patroni on a replica, delete pg_control, then restart Patroni so that\n   PostgreSQL fails to start due to the missing control file.\n3. Verify pebble logs on the replica record a pg_control startup failure.\n4. Run ``patronictl reinit`` inside the replica container to restore it from the primary.\n5. Confirm the replica recovers, that pg_control is present in the data directory,\n   and that data integrity is maintained across all units.\n</code></pre>\n","status":"passed","flaky":false,"newFailed":false,"newBroken":false,"newPassed":false,"retriesCount":1,"retriesStatusChange":true,"beforeStages":[{"name":"juju","time":{"start":1779846670162,"stop":1779846670162,"duration":0},"status":"passed","steps":[],"attachments":[],"parameters":[],"shouldDisplayMessage":false,"stepsCount":0,"atta